= Export Maya nParticles Cache =

"""Exports Houdini point geometry as a Maya nParticle cache (.xml + .mc files)."""

== Overview ==

This node bakes a Houdini point sequence into the Maya nCache format
(one `.mc` file per frame plus an `.xml` descriptor).  The resulting files
can be loaded in Maya via __nCache > Attach Existing Cache__ on an nParticle
object.

The following Houdini point attributes are exported when present:

table>>
    tr>>
        th>> Houdini attribute
        th>> Maya channel
        th>> Type
    tr>>
        td>> `P`
        td>> `position`
        td>> FloatVectorArray
    tr>>
        td>> `id`
        td>> `id`
        td>> DoubleArray
    tr>>
        td>> `v`
        td>> `velocity`
        td>> FloatVectorArray
    tr>>
        td>> `age`
        td>> `age`
        td>> DoubleArray
    tr>>
        td>> `life`
        td>> `lifespanPP`
        td>> DoubleArray
    tr>>
        td>> `pscale`
        td>> `radiusPP`
        td>> DoubleArray
    tr>>
        td>> `Cd`
        td>> `rgbPP`
        td>> FloatVectorArray
    tr>>
        td>> `Alpha`
        td>> `opacityPP`
        td>> DoubleArray
    tr>>
        td>> `rotation`
        td>> `rotationPP`
        td>> FloatVectorArray

A synthetic `count` channel (particle count per frame) is always written.

== Particle Name and Maya Node Naming ==

The __Particle Name__ parameter is the single most important setting for
Maya compatibility.

The value you enter here — call it `<name>` — determines the prefix of every
channel written into the cache:

{{{
channel names = <name>Shape_id
                <name>Shape_count
                <name>Shape_position
                <name>Shape_velocity
                ...
}}}

Maya's nCache system identifies which nParticle object a cache belongs to by
matching this prefix against the nParticle *shape node name*.  The shape node
must be named exactly `<name>Shape`.

:tip:
    Before exporting, check the name of your Maya nParticle shape node in
    Maya's Outliner (with __Shapes__ visible).  If it reads `nParticleShape`,
    set __Particle Name__ to `nParticle`.  If it reads `smokeShape`, set it
    to `smoke`, and so on.

Example:

table>>
    tr>>
        th>> Particle Name
        th>> Cache channel prefix
        th>> Required Maya shape name
    tr>>
        td>> `nParticle`
        td>> `nParticleShape_*`
        td>> `nParticleShape`
    tr>>
        td>> `particle`
        td>> `particleShape_*`
        td>> `particleShape`
    tr>>
        td>> `dust`
        td>> `dustShape_*`
        td>> `dustShape`

If the prefix does not match the Maya shape name, Maya silently skips the
cache and the particles will not play back from the file.

== Parameters ==

Start Frame:
    First frame to cache.

End Frame:
    Last frame to cache (inclusive).

Evaluation Rate:
    Fraction of a frame between successive cache samples.  `1` = one sample
    per frame.  `0.5` = two samples per frame (sub-frame caching).

XML:
    Full path to the output `.xml` descriptor file, including filename and
    extension.  The per-frame `.mc` files are written to the same directory
    with the pattern `<base>Frame<N>.mc`.

Particle Name:
    #id: particle_name

    Base name of the particle system.  The HDA appends `Shape` internally,
    so the value `nParticle` produces a shape prefix of `nParticleShape`.

    This value must match the nParticle shape node name in your Maya scene.
    See __Particle Name and Maya Node Naming__ above for details.

Cache:
    Click to start the export.  Houdini will step through every frame in the
    range, collect point data, and write the binary `.mc` files in parallel
    threads.  A progress dialog allows cancellation.

Python Module Path:
    Path to `nCache.py`.  Required at runtime; the HDA loads the module from
    this path each time __Cache__ is pressed so that the script can be updated
    without reimporting the HDA.

== How to Attach the Cache in Maya ==

# Create or select the nParticle object whose shape name matches your
  __Particle Name__ setting.
# In Maya, go to __FX > nCache > Attach Existing Cache__.
# Select the `.xml` file exported by this HDA.
# Maya reads the XML, finds the matching nParticle by channel prefix, and
  wires up the `cacheFile` node automatically.

:note:
    If you use __File > Import__ instead of __Attach Existing Cache__, Maya
    will not set up the nParticle cache connections and the file will appear
    to load without effect.
